  "@type": "sc:Dataset",
  "name": "skewECA, \u03b1ECA, stocECA, and tempECA: Benchmark Datasets for CA Identification under Noise",
  "description": "Eight benchmark datasets in two categories for the cellular automata identification problem. Four identification datasets (alphaECA, skewECA, stocECA, tempECA) spanning four noise types (alpha-asynchronous, s-skewed, stochastic, temporal-stochastic) across 256 ECA rules partitioned into 179 training and 77 test rules (seed=42, strictly disjoint). alphaECA and skewECA are pre-generated with two-phase structure: Phase 1 synchronous baseline and Phase 2 stratified across all noise levels, yielding 125,300 training and 23,100 test samples each. stocECA and tempECA generate training data on-the-fly (8,000 samples/epoch over 160 epochs = 1,280,000 training samples) with fixed test sets of 10,000 samples each. Four knowledge-check datasets (alphaK, skewK, stocK, tempK) contain 200 questions each across three difficulty levels (easy, medium, hard) in MCQ and short-answer formats, designed to verify that LLM failures on identification reflect structural limitations rather than missing domain knowledge. All datasets are fully synthetic, generated from ECA simulations. Reproducible from seed=42 using numpy.random.default_rng.",
  "conformsTo": [
    "http://mlcommons.org/croissant/1.1",
    "http://mlcommons.org/croissant/RAI/1.0"
  ],
  "citeAs": "Dataset Creator. (2026). skewECA, \u03b1ECA, stocECA, and tempECA: Benchmark Datasets for CA Identification under Noise Dataset. Generated with automated type inference.",
  "creator": {
    "@type": "sc:Person",
    "name": "Anonymous Author",
    "email": "anonymous@example.com"
  },
  "datePublished": "2026-05-04",
  "license": "https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/",
  "rai:dataBiases": "All data is fully synthetically generated from elementary cellular automata simulations. No human subjects, demographic data, or real-world collection is involved. The 256 ECA rules are partitioned under a fixed seed (seed=42) with a 70/30 train/test split that approximately preserves Wolfram class proportions (C1: ~9%, C2: ~71%, C3+C4: ~20%), with C3+C4 rules slightly over-represented in the test set (22.1% vs 19.5% overall) making the test set marginally harder. Rule sampling covers all four Wolfram behavioural classes. For stocECA and tempECA, training-time pair sampling provides implicit but not guaranteed class-combination balance, while fixed test sets are explicitly stratified across all six Wolfram class-pair combinations.",
  "rai:dataLimitations": "Datasets are restricted to one-dimensional elementary cellular automata as a proxy for natural systems and may not generalize to higher-dimensional, continuous, or real-world physical and biological systems. Four specific noise types are studied; other noise models are out of scope. The identification problem has known fundamental identifiability limits: for tempECA, the system (R1,R2,tau) is statistically indistinguishable from (R2,R1,1-tau), making rule pair orientation unrecoverable at tau=0.5. For stocECA, the within-variance signal is zero for agreeing rule pairs. Rule 204 (identity rule) renders alpha-noise unrecoverable from any cell-change statistic. Class C1 (null/uniform) rules produce nearly uninformative orbits at low noise rates. stocECA and tempECA use continuous noise parameters with approximately uniform but not exactly stratified test distributions. Training data for stocECA and tempECA is never stored to disk and is regenerated each epoch.",
  "url": "https://anonymous.4open.science/r/LLM_NOISE-9DC1",
  "version": "1.0.0",
